definition.value: The open-chain form of D-fructose.
A C-nitro compound with formula C6H(6-n)(NO2)n (n can be from 1 up to 6, but is usually 1, 2 or 3). A closed class.
Any member of the class of pyrimidine ribonucleosides in which the pyrimidine moiety consists of 2-amino-4-hydroxypyrimidine or its derivatives.
Anthracyclines are polyketides that have a tetrahydronaphthacenedione ring structure attached by a glycosidic linkage to the amino sugar daunosamine.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is heptane substituted at positions 1 and 7 by carboxy groups.
A polyketide based on a tetracene ring structure.

A L-histidine derivative that is N(alpha),N(alpha),N(alpha)-trimethyl-L-histidine in which the hydrogen at position 2 on the imdazole ring is replaced by a mercapto group. A naturally occurring metabolite of histidine synthesized by bacteria and fungi with antioxidant properties. It is found ubiquitously in plants and animals and is present in many human foodstuffs.
A tetritol that is butane substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 1, 2, 3 and 4.
The D-enantiomer of threitol.
A monovalent inorganic anion that consists of triphosphoric acid in which one of the five OH groups has been deprotonated.
A divalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of two protons from triphosphoric acid.
A trivalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of three protons from triphosphoric acid.
A cis-1-acetyl-4-(4-{[2-(2,4-dichlorophenyl)-2-(1H-imidazol-1-ylmethyl)-1,3-dioxolan-4-yl]methoxy}phenyl)piperazine which dioxolane moiety has (2R,4S)-configuration.
A dioxolane that is 1,3-dioxolane which is substituted at positions 2, 2, and 4 by imidazol-1-ylmethyl, 2,4-dichlorophenyl, and [para-(4-acetylpiperazin-1-yl)phenoxy]methyl groups, respectively.

Either of the two diastereoisomers of 1-acetyl-4-(4-{[2-(2,4-dichlorophenyl)-2-(1H-imidazol-1-ylmethyl)-1,3-dioxolan-4-yl]methoxy}phenyl)piperazine in which the imidazol-1-ylmethyl group and the aryloxymethyl group are in a trans relationship to each other - i.e. they are on opposite sides of the plane of the dioxolane ring. (N.B. The antifungal drug ketoconazole is a racemic mixture of the two cis diastereoisomers.)
Compounds of structure RSSR'.
A 1-acetyl-4-(4-{[2-(2,4-dichlorophenyl)-2-(1H-imidazol-1-ylmethyl)-1,3-dioxolan-4-yl]methoxy}phenyl)piperazine in which the dioxolane ring has R configuration at positions 2 and 4.
A C-nitro compound that is entacapone in which the phenolic hydroxy group that is meta to the nitro group has been converted to the corresponding ethyl ether.
A C-nitro compound that is entacapone in which the phenolic hydroxy group that is meta to the nitro group has been converted to the corresponding methyl ether.
A member of the class of benzaldehydes that is vanillin in which the hydrogen ortho- to the hydroxy group is substituted by a nitro group.
The simplest member of the class of methanediols that is methane in which two of the hydrogens have been substituted by hydroxy groups.
A monocarboxylic acid that is 3-phenylpropionic acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 4. It is a metabolite of caffeic acid and exhibits antioxidant activity.
A member of the class of benzaldehydes that is vanillin in which the methoxy group is replaced by an ethoxy group.
An oxopurine in which the purine ring is substituted by oxo groups at positions 2 and 6 and N-7 is protonated.
A hydroxycoumarin that is the 6-O-beta-D-glucoside of esculetin.
A methoxycinnamic acid having a single methoxy substituent at the 4-position on the phenyl ring.
Esters or salts of methanesulfonic acid.
An arsenate ion resulting from the removal of two protons from arsenic acid.
An arsenate ion resulting from the removal of one proton from arsenic acid.
A metal chloride salt with a Li(+) counterion.
The L-stereoisomer of sorbopyranose.
